WEBVTT

00:20.140 --> 00:23.100
CHAPTER 37 THE REAPER WHOSE NAME IS DEATH

00:24.180 --> 00:26.480
Matthew, Matthew, what is the matter?

00:27.140 --> 00:28.160
Matthew, are you sick?

00:28.160 --> 00:34.240
It was Marilla who spoke, alarm in every jerky word. Anne came through the hall,

00:34.480 --> 00:39.720
her hands full of white narcissus. It was long before Anne could love the sight or order of

00:39.720 --> 00:45.200
white narcissus again. In time to hear her, Anne to see Matthew standing in the porch doorway,

00:45.920 --> 00:52.000
a folded paper in his hand, and his face strangely drawn and grey. Anne dropped her

00:52.000 --> 00:57.760
flowers and sprang across the kitchen to him at the same moment as Marilla. They were both too late,

00:57.760 --> 01:01.420
before they could reach him. Matthew had fallen across the threshold.

01:02.860 --> 01:08.120
He's fainted, gasped Marilla. Anne, run for Martin. Quick, quick, he's at the barn.

01:09.000 --> 01:14.900
Martin, the hired hand, who had just driven home from the post office, started at once for the

01:14.900 --> 01:21.720
doctor, calling at Orchard Slope on his way to send Mr. and Mrs. Barry over. Mrs. Lind, who was

01:21.720 --> 01:26.860
there on an errand, came too. They found Anne and Marilla distractedly trying to restore

01:26.860 --> 01:33.560
Matthew to consciousness. Mrs. Lind pushed them gently aside, tried his pulse, and then laid her

01:33.560 --> 01:39.540
ear over his heart. She looked at their anxious faces sorrowfully, and the tears came into her

01:39.540 --> 01:48.600
eyes. Oh, Marilla, she said gravely, I don't think we can do anything for him. Mrs. Lind,

01:48.600 --> 01:56.180
you don't think, you can't think Matthew is, is. Anne could not say the dreadful word. She turned

01:56.180 --> 02:04.020
sick and pallid. Child, yes, I'm afraid of it. Look at his face. When you've seen that look as

02:04.020 --> 02:09.980
often as I have, you'll know what it means. Anne looked at the still face and there beheld the seal

02:09.980 --> 02:16.420
of the great presence. When the doctor came, he said that death had been instantaneous and probably

02:16.420 --> 02:23.500
painless, caused in all likelihood by some sudden shock. The secret of the shock was discovered to

02:23.500 --> 02:29.600
be in the paper Matthew had held and which Martin had brought from the office that morning. It

02:29.600 --> 02:36.080
contained an account of the failure of the Abbey Bank. The news spread quickly through Avonlea,

02:36.220 --> 02:41.300
and all day friends and neighbours thronged green gables and came and went on errands of kindness

02:41.300 --> 02:48.160
for the dead and living. For the first time, shy, quiet, Matthew Cuthbert was a person of

02:48.160 --> 02:53.910
central importance. The white majesty of death had fallen on him and set him apart as one crowned.

02:54.900 --> 03:01.080
When the calm night came softly down over green gables, the old house was hushed and tranquil.

03:01.860 --> 03:08.520
In the parlour lay Matthew Cuthbert, in his coffin, his long grey hair framing his placid face,

03:08.520 --> 03:16.440
on which there was a little kindly smile, as if he but slept, dreaming pleasant dreams.

03:17.280 --> 03:22.600
There were flowers about him, sweet old-fashioned flowers which his mother had planted in the

03:22.600 --> 03:29.520
homestead garden in her bridal days and for which Matthew had always had a secret, wordless love.

03:30.500 --> 03:36.560
Anne had gathered them and brought them to him, her anguished, tearless eyes burning in her white

03:36.560 --> 03:43.720
face. It was the last thing she could do for him. The berries and Mrs. Lynn stayed with them that

03:43.720 --> 03:51.580
night. Diana, going to the east gable, where Anne was standing at her window, said gently,

03:52.520 --> 03:59.780
Anne dear, would you like to have me sleep with you tonight? Thank you, Diana. Anne looked earnestly

03:59.780 --> 04:05.720
into her friend's face. I think you wouldn't misunderstand me when I say I want to be alone.

04:06.560 --> 04:14.200
I'm not afraid. I haven't been alone one minute since it happened. And I want to be. I want to be

04:14.200 --> 04:22.740
quite silent and quiet and try to realize it. I can't realize it. Half the time it seems to me

04:22.740 --> 04:28.940
that Matthew can't be dead, and the other half it seems as if he must have been dead for a long time

04:28.940 --> 04:34.660
and I've had this horrible, dull ache ever since. Diana did not quite understand.

04:35.740 --> 04:42.180
Marilla's impassioned grief, breaking all the bounds of national reserve, and lifelong habit

04:42.180 --> 04:49.260
in its stormy rush. She could comprehend better than Anne's tearless agony, but she went away

04:49.260 --> 04:55.860
kindly, leaving Anne alone to keep her first vigil with sorrow. Anne hoped that the tears

04:55.860 --> 05:00.980
would come in solitude. It seemed to her a terrible thing that she could not shed a tear for Matthew,

05:00.980 --> 05:06.080
whom she had loved so much and who had been so kind to her. Matthew, who had walked with

05:06.080 --> 05:11.960
her last evening at sunset and was now lying in the dim room below, with that awful piece on his

05:11.960 --> 05:18.140
brow. But no tears came at first, even when she knelt by her window in the darkness and prayed,

05:18.580 --> 05:24.460
looking up to the stars beyond the hills. No tears, only the same horrible dull ache of misery

05:24.460 --> 05:30.260
that kept on aching until she fell asleep, worn out with the day's pain and excitement.

05:30.980 --> 05:36.300
In the night she awakened, with the stillness and the darkness about her, and the recollection of

05:36.300 --> 05:41.600
the day came over her like a wave of sorrow. She could see Matthew's face smiling at her,

05:41.760 --> 05:47.080
as he had smiled when they parted at the gate that last evening. She could hear his voice saying,

05:47.560 --> 05:53.400
My girl, my girl that I'm proud of. Then the tears came and Anne wept her heart out.

05:53.840 --> 05:56.000
Marilla heard her and crept in to comfort her.

05:57.260 --> 06:06.920
There, there. Don't cry so, dearie. It can't bring him back. It isn't right to cry so. I knew that

06:06.920 --> 06:12.520
today, but I couldn't help it then. He'd always been such a good kind brother to me. But God knows

06:12.520 --> 06:19.700
best. Oh, just let me cry, Marilla, sobbed Anne. The tears don't hurt me like that ache did. Stay

06:19.700 --> 06:27.020
for a while with me and keep your arms around me. So. I couldn't have Diana's day. She's good and

06:27.020 --> 06:32.340
kind and sweet, but it's not her sorrow. She's outside of it and she couldn't come close enough

06:32.340 --> 06:38.600
to my heart to help me. It's our sorrow, yours and mine. Oh, Marilla, what will we do without him?

06:39.600 --> 06:44.700
We've got each other, Anne. I don't know what I'd do if you weren't here, if you'd never come.

06:44.700 --> 06:48.760
Oh, Anne, I know I've been kind of strict and harsh with you maybe,

06:49.120 --> 06:55.060
but you mustn't think I didn't love you as well as Matthew did, for all that. I want to tell you

06:55.060 --> 07:00.920
now when I can. It's never been easy for me to say things out of my heart, but at times like this

07:00.920 --> 07:06.860
it's easier. I love you as dear as if you were my own flesh and blood, and you've been my joy and

07:06.860 --> 07:13.720
comfort ever since you came to Green Gables. Two days afterwards they carried Matthew Cuthbert over

07:13.720 --> 07:19.600
his homestead threshold and away from the fields he had tilled and the orchards he had loved and

07:19.600 --> 07:26.260
the trees he had planted. And then Avonlea settled back to its usual placidity, and even at Green

07:26.260 --> 07:32.260
Gables affairs slipped into their old groove and work was done and duties fulfilled with regularity

07:32.260 --> 07:40.080
as before, although always with the aching sense of loss in all familiar things. Anne, new to grief,

07:40.080 --> 07:46.040
thought it almost sad that it could be so, that they could go on in the old way without Matthew.

07:46.660 --> 07:51.900
She felt something like shame and remorse when she discovered that the sunrises behind the firs

07:52.440 --> 07:58.740
and the pale pink buds opening in the garden gave her the old inrush of gladness when she saw them,

07:59.180 --> 08:03.640
that Diana's visits were pleasant to her and that Diana's merry words and ways

08:03.640 --> 08:10.440
moved her to laughter and smiles, that, in brief, the beautiful world of blossom and love and

08:10.440 --> 08:14.880
friendship had lost none of its power to please her fancy and thrill her heart,

08:15.480 --> 08:18.560
that life still called to her with many insistent voices.

08:19.260 --> 08:24.900
It seems like disloyalty to Matthew somehow to find pleasure in these things now that he has gone,

08:25.240 --> 08:29.900
she said wistfully to Mrs. Allen one evening when they were together in the man's garden.

08:30.460 --> 08:36.620
I miss him so much, all the time, and yet Mrs. Allen, the world and life seem very beautiful

08:36.620 --> 08:42.260
and interesting to me for all. Today Diana said something funny and I found myself laughing,

08:42.940 --> 08:49.380
I thought when it happened I could never laugh again, and somehow it seems as if I oughtn't to.

08:50.460 --> 08:59.140
When Matthew was here he liked to hear you laugh, he liked to know you had found pleasure in the

08:59.140 --> 09:05.660
world, and he likes to know it just the same. I am sure we should not shut our hearts against

09:05.660 --> 09:11.680
the healing influences that nature offers us, but I can understand your feeling. I think we all

09:11.680 --> 09:16.860
experience the same thing, we resent the thought that anything can please us when someone we love

09:16.860 --> 09:22.200
is no longer here to share the pleasure with us, and we almost feel as if we were unfaithful to

09:22.200 --> 09:28.440
our sorrow when we find our interest in life returning to us. I was down to the graveyard

09:28.440 --> 09:33.980
to plant a rose bush on Matthew's grave this afternoon, said Anne dreamily. I took a slip

09:33.980 --> 09:39.900
of the little white scotch rose bush his mother brought out from Scotland long ago. Matthew always

09:39.900 --> 09:45.700
liked those roses the best, they were so small and sweet on their thorny stems. It made me feel glad

09:45.700 --> 09:50.720
that I could plant it by his grave, as if I were doing something that must please him in taking it

09:50.720 --> 09:56.460
there to be near him. I hope he has roses like them in heaven. Perhaps the souls of all those

09:56.460 --> 10:02.880
white roses that he has loved for so many years were all there to meet him. I must go home now,

10:03.120 --> 10:05.620
Marilla is all alone and she gets lonely at twilight.

10:06.580 --> 10:11.300
She will be lonelier still, I fear, when you go away again to college, said Mrs. Allen.

10:12.300 --> 10:16.040
Anne did not reply. She said good night and went slowly back to Green Gables.

10:16.800 --> 10:22.280
Marilla was sitting on the front doorsteps and Anne sat down beside her. The door was open behind

10:22.280 --> 10:29.100
them, held back by a big pink conch shell with hints of sea sunsets in its smooth inner convolutions.

10:29.680 --> 10:34.580
Anne gathered some sprays of pale yellow honeysuckle and put them in her hair. She

10:34.580 --> 10:40.360
liked the delicious hint of fragrance as some aerial benediction above her every time she moved.

10:41.120 --> 10:47.000
Dr. Spencer was here while you were away, Marilla said. He says that the specialist will be in town

10:47.000 --> 10:53.660
tomorrow and he insists that I must go in and have my eyes examined. I suppose I'd better go and have

10:53.660 --> 10:59.100
it over. I'll be more than thankful if the man can give me the right kind of glasses to suit my eyes.

10:59.760 --> 11:04.540
You won't mind staying here alone while I'm away, will you? Martin will have to drive me in and

11:04.540 --> 11:10.900
there's ironing and baking to do. I shall be all right. Diana will come over for company for me.

11:11.020 --> 11:15.380
I shall attend to the ironing and baking beautifully. You needn't fear that I'll

11:15.380 --> 11:21.400
torch the handkerchiefs or flavor the cake with liniment. Marilla laughed. What a girl you were

11:21.400 --> 11:26.660
for making mistakes in them days, Anne. You were always getting into scrapes. I did used to think

11:26.660 --> 11:32.900
you were possessed. Do you mind the time you dyed your hair? Yes, indeed, I shall never forget it,

11:33.080 --> 11:38.280
smiled Anne, touching the heavy braid of her hair that was wound about her shapely head.

11:38.940 --> 11:43.720
I laugh a little now sometimes when I think what a worry my hair used to be to me,

11:43.720 --> 11:49.880
but I don't laugh much because it was a very real trouble then. I did suffer terribly over my hair

11:49.880 --> 11:54.620
and my freckles. My freckles are really gone and people are nice enough to tell me my hair is

11:54.620 --> 12:00.620
open now. But old Josie Pie, she informed me yesterday that she really thought it was redder

12:00.620 --> 12:05.940
than ever, or at least my black dress made it look redder, and she asked me if people who had

12:05.940 --> 12:11.800
red hair ever got used to having it. Marilla, I've almost decided to give up trying to like Josie Pie.

12:12.360 --> 12:18.140
I've made what I would once have called a heroic effort to like her, but Josie Pie won't be liked.

12:18.960 --> 12:24.700
Josie is a pious, said Marilla sharply. So she can't help being disagreeable. I suppose people

12:24.700 --> 12:30.980
of that kind serve some useful purpose in society, but I must say I don't know what it is anymore than

12:30.980 --> 12:37.180
I know the use of thistles. Is Josie going to teach? No, she is going back to Queen's next year.

12:37.660 --> 12:43.500
So are Moody Spurgeon and Charlie Sloan. Jane and Ruby are going to teach and they have both

12:43.500 --> 12:49.580
got schools. Jane at New Bridge and Ruby at some place up west. Gilbert Blythe is going to teach

12:49.580 --> 12:57.640
too, isn't he? Yes, briefly. What a nice looking fellow he is, said Marilla absently. I saw him

12:57.640 --> 13:03.160
in church last Sunday and he seemed so tall and manly. He looks a lot like his father did at the

13:03.160 --> 13:09.220
same age. John Blythe was a nice boy. We used to be real good friends, he and I. People called him

13:09.220 --> 13:16.040
my beau. Anne looked up with swift interest. Oh Marilla, and what happened? Why didn't you?

13:16.680 --> 13:22.520
We had a quarrel. I wouldn't forgive him when he asked me to. I meant to, but after a while,

13:22.960 --> 13:29.580
but I was sulky and angry and I wanted to punish him first. He never came back. The Blythes were

13:29.580 --> 13:36.080
mighty independent. But I always felt rather sorry. I've always kind of wished I'd forgiven

13:36.080 --> 13:41.160
him when I had the chance. So you've had a bit of romance in your life too, said Anne softly.

13:42.000 --> 13:46.220
Yes, I suppose you might call it that. You wouldn't think so to look at me, would you?

13:46.620 --> 13:51.360
But you could never tell about people from their outsides. Everybody has forgot about me and John.

13:51.800 --> 13:56.040
I'd forgotten myself, but it all came back to me when I saw Gilbert last Sunday.

